This behavior violates RFC 9112, Section 5.1, which states that "No whitespace is allowed between the field name and the colon." By stripping this whitespace instead of rejecting the malformed header, `aiohttp` will accept headers that a compliant proxy would reject (e.g., `"Header-Name : value"`). This discrepancy in parsing can be abused to perform HTTP request smuggling (CWE-444). An attacker could craft a request that is interpreted differently by the frontend proxy and the `aiohttp` backend, leading to a desynchronization of the request stream.

This is a confirmed true positive. I will submit this finding now. After this, as it is my final iteration, I will complete the review.

